04228nam a22006615i 9789048501311DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20082009ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485013117 a10.1515/97890485013112doi  a(DE-B1597)534346  a(OCoLC)302405578  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a3631 aNetherlands Scientific Council for Government Policy, The Netherlands Scientific Council for Government Policy (WRR), eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInfrastructures :bTime to Invest /cThe Netherlands Scientific Council for Government Policy (WRR) Netherlands Scientific Council for Government Policy. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWRR Rapporten ;v8100tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tSUMMARY IN DUTCH -- tEXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tPREFACE -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Regime Change And Investment In infrastructures -- t3. A New Constellation Of Actors -- t4. Infrastructures In A Multi-Level Arena -- t5. Regime Change And Public Values In Infrastructures -- t6. Regime Change And Investment In Energy Infrastructure -- t7. Conclusion And Recommendations -- tAnnex. Characteristics Of The Physical Infrastructures: An Indicative Inventory -- tAbbreviations -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAll sectors of the Dutch infrastructures have undergone a degree of commercialisation, liberalisation or privatisation over the last ten to twenty years. Where in the past the infrastructure landscape was dominated by public monopolies, the ownership and management of infrastructures is today shared by several public and private sector players. The original goals of this 'regime change' have in many cases been achieved: greater efficiency, a greater focus on the customer and more choice for consumers. The question is whether this emphasis on current consumer interests allows enough scope to achieve long-term objectives which affect the whole of our society: innovation, long-term availability and sustainability of infrastructures. This is of crucial importance for economic and social development, which is coming under increasing pressure due to the combined impact of the exhaustion of natural resources and climate change. The transition to a sustainable future demands substantial investment in infrastructures, which cannot be taken for granted in the present situation. The WRR has investigated how these investments could be safeguarded in the long term, whilst retaining the efficiency of the infrastructures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048501311zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048501311423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048501311.jpg  a978-3-11-070067-1  AUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK